Added for organizational purposes, to identify all properties defined in the Land Use ontology.

owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:comment: A Parcel may have a number of employed residents that is subject to change over time.
A Parcel may have some population that is subject to change over time.
A parcel may have some population of residents at a given point in time.

owl:ObjectProperty.dc:description: Added for organizational purposes, to identify properties defined in the iCity-Organization ontology.
Added for organizational purposes, to identify properties defined in the Person ontology.
Added for organizational purposes, to capture the properties reused from Schema.org. Notice that since we cannot import schema.org we must manually reference the individual IRIs.

owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:comment: Relation between an Actuation and the property of a FeatureOfInterest it is acting upon.
owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:label: acts on property
owl:ObjectProperty.skos:definition: Relation between an Actuation and the property of a FeatureOfInterest it is acting upon.
owl:ObjectProperty.skos:example: In the activity (Actuation) of automatically closing a window if the temperature in a room drops below 20 degrees Celsius, the property on which the Actuator acts upon is the state of the window as it changes from being open to being closed.

owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:comment: A relation between an Observation and the entity whose quality was observed, or between an Actuation and the entity whose property was modified, or between an act of Sampling and the entity that was sampled.
owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:label: has feature of interest
owl:ObjectProperty.skos:definition: A relation between an Observation and the entity whose quality was observed, or between an Actuation and the entity whose property was modified, or between an act of Sampling and the entity that was sampled.
owl:ObjectProperty.skos:example: For example, in an Observation of the weight of a person, the FeatureOfInterest is the person and the property is its weight.

owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:comment: Relation linking an Observation or Actuation or act of Sampling and a Result or Sample.
owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:label: has result
owl:ObjectProperty.skos:definition: Relation linking an Observation or Actuation or act of Sampling and a Result or Sample.

owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:comment: Relation between a FeatureOfInterest and the Sample used to represent it.
owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:label: has sample
owl:ObjectProperty.skos:definition: Relation between a FeatureOfInterest and the Sample used to represent it.

owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:comment: Relation between a Platform and a Sensor, Actuator, Sampler, or Platform, hosted or mounted on it.
owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:label: hosts
owl:ObjectProperty.skos:definition: Relation between a Platform and a Sensor, Actuator, Sampler, or Platform, hosted or mounted on it.

owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:comment: Relation between an ActuatableProperty of a FeatureOfInterest and an Actuation changing its state.
owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:label: is acted on by
owl:ObjectProperty.skos:definition: Relation between an ActuatableProperty of a FeatureOfInterest and an Actuation changing its state.
owl:ObjectProperty.skos:example: In the activity (Actuation) of automatically closing a window if the temperature in a room drops below 20 degrees Celsius, the property on which the Actuator acts upon is the state of the window as it changes from being open to being closed.

owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:comment: A relation between a FeatureOfInterest and an Observation about it, an Actuation acting on it, or an act of Sampling that sampled it.
owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:label: is feature of interest of
owl:ObjectProperty.skos:definition: A relation between a FeatureOfInterest and an Observation about it, an Actuation acting on it, or an act of Sampling that sampled it.

owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:comment: Relation between a Sensor, Actuator, Sampler, or Platform, and the Platform that it is mounted on or hosted by.
owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:label: is hosted by
owl:ObjectProperty.skos:definition: Relation between a Sensor, Actuator, Sampler, or Platform, and the Platform that it is mounted on or hosted by.

owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:comment: Relation between an ObservableProperty and the Sensor able to observe it.
owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:label: is observed by
owl:ObjectProperty.skos:definition: Relation between an ObservableProperty and the Sensor able to observe it.

owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:comment: Relation linking a Result to the Observation or Actuation or act of Sampling that created or caused it.
owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:label: is result of
owl:ObjectProperty.skos:definition: Relation linking a Result to the Observation or Actuation or act of Sampling that created or caused it.

owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:comment: Relation from a Sample to the FeatureOfInterest that it is intended to be representative of.
owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:label: is sample of
owl:ObjectProperty.skos:definition: Relation from a Sample to the FeatureOfInterest that it is intended to be representative of.

owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:comment: Relation between an Actuator and the Actuation it has made.
owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:label: made actuation
owl:ObjectProperty.skos:definition: Relation between an Actuator and the Actuation it has made.

owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:comment: Relation linking an Actuation to the Actuator that made that Actuation.
owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:label: made by actuator
owl:ObjectProperty.skos:definition: Relation linking an Actuation to the Actuator that made that Actuation.

owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:comment: Relation linking an act of Sampling to the Sampler (sampling device or entity) that made it.
owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:label: made by sampler
owl:ObjectProperty.skos:definition: Relation linking an act of Sampling to the Sampler (sampling device or entity) that made it.

owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:comment: Relation between an Observation and the Sensor which made the Observation.
owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:label: made by sensor
owl:ObjectProperty.skos:definition: Relation between an Observation and the Sensor which made the Observation.

owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:comment: Relation between a Sensor and an Observation made by the Sensor.
owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:label: made observation
owl:ObjectProperty.skos:definition: Relation between a Sensor and an Observation made by the Sensor.

owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:comment: Relation between a Sampler (sampling device or entity) and the Sampling act it performed.
owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:label: made sampling
owl:ObjectProperty.skos:definition: Relation between a Sampler (sampling device or entity) and the Sampling act it performed.

owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:comment: Relation linking an Observation to the property that was observed. The ObservableProperty should be a property of the FeatureOfInterest (linked by hasFeatureOfInterest) of this Observation.
owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:label: observed property
owl:ObjectProperty.skos:definition: Relation linking an Observation to the property that was observed. The ObservableProperty should be a property of the FeatureOfInterest (linked by hasFeatureOfInterest) of this Observation.

owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:comment: Relation between a Sensor and an ObservableProperty that it is capable of sensing.
owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:label: observes
owl:ObjectProperty.skos:definition: Relation between a Sensor and an ObservableProperty that it is capable of sensing.

owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:comment: The time that the Result of an Observation, Actuation or Sampling applies to the FeatureOfInterest. Not necessarily the same as the resultTime. May be an Interval or an Instant, or some other compound TemporalEntity.
owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:label: phenomenon time
owl:ObjectProperty.skos:definition: The time that the Result of an Observation, Actuation or Sampling applies to the FeatureOfInterest. Not necessarily the same as the resultTime. May be an Interval or an Instant, or some other compound TemporalEntity.

owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:comment: A relation to link to a re-usable Procedure used in making an Observation, an Actuation, or a Sample, typically through a Sensor, Actuator or Sampler.
owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:label: used procedure
owl:ObjectProperty.skos:definition: A relation to link to a re-usable Procedure used in making an Observation, an Actuation, or a Sample, typically through a Sensor, Actuator or Sampler.

owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:comment: Relation between a Deployment and the Platform on which the Systems are deployed.
owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:label: deployed on platform
owl:ObjectProperty.skos:definition: Relation between a Deployment and the Platform on which the Systems are deployed.

owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:comment: Relation between a Deployment and a deployed System.
owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:label: deployed system
owl:ObjectProperty.skos:definition: Relation between a Deployment and a deployed System.

owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:comment: A relation from a Sensor to the Stimulus that the Sensor can detect. The Stimulus itself will be serving as a proxy for some ObservableProperty.
owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:label: detects
owl:ObjectProperty.skos:definition: A relation from a Sensor to the Stimulus that the Sensor detects. The Stimulus itself will be serving as a proxy for some ObservableProperty.

owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:comment: A relation between some aspect of an entity and a Property.
owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:label: for property
owl:ObjectProperty.skos:definition: A relation between some aspect of an entity and a Property.
owl:ObjectProperty.skos:example: For example, from a Sensor to the properties it can observe; from an Actuator to the properties it can act on; from a Deployment to the properties it was installed to observe or act on; from a SystemCapability to the Property the capability is described for.

owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:comment: Relation between a System and a Deployment, recording that the System is deployed in that Deployment.
owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:label: has deployment
owl:ObjectProperty.skos:definition: Relation between a System and a Deployment, recording that the System is deployed in that Deployment.

owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:comment: Relation between a Procedure and an Input to it.
owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:label: has input
owl:ObjectProperty.skos:definition: Relation between a Procedure and an Input to it.

owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:comment: Relation between a Procedure and an Output of it.
owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:label: has output
owl:ObjectProperty.skos:definition: Relation between a Procedure and an Output of it.

owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:comment: Relation between an entity and a Property of that entity.
owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:label: has property
owl:ObjectProperty.skos:definition: Relation between an entity and a Property of that entity.

owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:comment: Relation between a System and its component parts.
owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:label: has subsystem
owl:ObjectProperty.skos:definition: Relation between a System and its component parts.

owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:comment: Relation between a Procedure (an algorithm, procedure or method) and an entity that implements that Procedure in some executable way.
owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:label: implemented by
owl:ObjectProperty.skos:definition: Relation between a Procedure (an algorithm, procedure or method) and an entity that implements that Procedure in some executable way.
owl:ObjectProperty.skos:example: For example, the relationship between a scientific measuring Procedure and a sensor that senses via that Procedure.

owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:comment: Relation between an entity that implements a Procedure in some executable way and the Procedure (an algorithm, procedure or method).
owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:label: implements
owl:ObjectProperty.skos:definition: Relation between an entity that implements a Procedure in some executable way and the Procedure (an algorithm, procedure or method).
owl:ObjectProperty.skos:example: For example, the relationship between a sensor and the scientific measuring Procedure via which it senses.

owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:comment: Relation between a Platform and a Deployment, meaning that the deployedSystems of the Deployment are hosted on the Platform.
owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:label: in deployment
owl:ObjectProperty.skos:definition: Relation between a Platform and a Deployment, meaning that the deployedSystems of the Deployment are hosted on the Platform.
owl:ObjectProperty.skos:example: For example, a relation between a buoy and a deployment of several Sensors.

owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:comment: Relation between a Property and the entity it belongs to.
owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:label: is property of
owl:ObjectProperty.skos:definition: Relation between a Property and the entity it belongs to.

owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:comment: A relation from a Stimulus to the Property that the Stimulus is serving as a proxy for.
owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:label: is proxy for
owl:ObjectProperty.skos:definition: A relation from a Stimulus to the Property that the Stimulus is serving as a proxy for.
owl:ObjectProperty.skos:example: For example, the expansion of quicksilver is a stimulus that serves as a proxy for some temperature property. An increase or decrease in the velocity of spinning cups on a wind sensor is serving as a proxy for the wind speed.

owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:comment: Relation between an Observation and the Stimulus that originated it.
owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:label: was originated by
owl:ObjectProperty.skos:definition: Relation between an Observation and the Stimulus that originated it.

owl:DatatypeProperty.dc:description: Added for organizational purposes, to identify data properties defined in the Building ontology.

owl:DatatypeProperty.rdfs:comment: The simple value of an Observation or Actuation or act of Sampling.
owl:DatatypeProperty.rdfs:label: has simple result
owl:DatatypeProperty.skos:definition: The simple value of an Observation or Actuation or act of Sampling.
owl:DatatypeProperty.skos:example: For instance, the values 23 or true.

owl:DatatypeProperty.rdfs:comment: The result time is the instant of time when the Observation, Actuation or Sampling activity was completed.
owl:DatatypeProperty.rdfs:label: result time
owl:DatatypeProperty.skos:definition: The result time is the instant of time when the Observation, Actuation or Sampling activity was completed.

owl:Class.dc:description: Building: A Building is a structure with some location in the urban system. The location of the Building in space may change due to construction, but the Parcel/Lot of land it is located on cannot. There are different types (subclasses) of buildings; House, Apartment Building, Office Building... A Building has an owner, which may be a Persons or some Organization. A Building has occupants, which may or may not be the same Persons or Firm who own it. A Building has a market value. A Building may provide some Parking. A Building has some Location. A Building has some height, some footprint area, and some floor area. The floor area is often greater than the footprint area as it accounts for the area of each floor of the building. However, floor area excludes unoccupied areas such as basements. These properties are considered variant as it is possible for a building to undergo construction to increase its dimensions. A Building contains one or many units.
Added for organizational purposes, to identify classes defined in the Building ontology.

BuildingUnit: A part of a Building which may be occupied by some Persons or Organization. A BuildingUnit has a size (square footage, number of rooms) A BuildingUnit may contain some Facilities, e.g. kitchen, bath.(Note that contain is distinct from the notion of including amenities, which may be part of the Tenure) A BuildingUnit has an address
Added for organizational purposes, to capture the classes reused from Schema.org. Notice that since we cannot import schema.org we must manually reference the individual IRIs.
A Dwelling Unit is occupied by a Household. A Dwelling Unit has a market value. A Dwelling Unit is located in some Building (e.g. House, Apartment,...) A Dwelling Unit has some Location.

A family has members who are Persons, and who are related via the has-spouse or has-child properties. We may define different types of Family (e.g. Immediate, Extended). Here, we simply make the commitment that it is a group of people who are connected via the has-spouse or has-child properties. From these, we can derive grandparents, aunts, uncles, etcetera. One question to consider is to what degree the general/extended Family concept makes sense or is useful. After a few generations the concept of a family will become quite large and confusing, with Persons belonging to many different Families. At a certain point it may be more useful to consider a relatedTo property between Persons, or only defining restricted subclasses of Family.

Added for organizational purposes, to capture the classes reused from the GCI-Shelters ontology. Notice that at this point in time we have not imported the entire GCI-Shelter Ontology and so we must manually reference the individual IRIs.

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A Household has one or more Persons as members. A Household occupies a particular Dwelling, according to some tenure type. It is defined by this location, so that if the members move (even collectively), the new residence constitutes a new Household. We do not make any commitment regarding the identity of the Persons, and in fact a Person may belong to more than one Household. Note that a Household, and likely many other classes may have different definitions in different contexts/applications. To address this we may be required to introduce specializations of the class (e.g. ILUTE_Household, TTS_Household) in future extensions.

owl:Class.dc:description: Added for organizational purposes, to identify classes defined in the Household ontology.

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Arrangements under which the occupant has the right to live in the dwelling unit, e.g. tenancy, owner-occupancy. To be defined in greater detail (if required) in future versions.

owl:Class.dc:description: A Parcel is a way of defining some area in an urban system. A Parcel has a Location. A Parcel may be classified as having some type of Land Use. There may be other types (subclasses) of Parcel, defined in more precise or different ways, such as a Zone.

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Agriculture and Agri-Foods Canada Classification is a type (subclass of) land use classification. The codes are based on the IPCC (International Panel on Climate Change) protocol.
Annual and perennial TBD: Should this be the same as the CLUMPCropland class?
Natural and human-made. TBD: should this be the same as the CLUMPWater class?

owl:Class.dc:description: A - Cropland
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: 'A' Cropland - Land used for annual field crops such as grain, oilseeds, sugar beets, tobacco, potatoes, field vegetables and canning crops. Associated fallow, and land being cleared for field crops are also included.

owl:Class.dc:description: Z - Water areas
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: 'Z' Additional code added during data integration for water areas based on the CLI shoreline maps.
The population of employed residents in a given area (Parcel)
Treed areas >1 ha in size
Wetland with forest cover
Natural grass and shrubs used for cattle grazing
Natural grass and shrubs with no apparent use (forest openings, alpine meadows, tundra, etc.)

owl:Class.dc:description: H - Horticulture
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: 'H' Horticulture, poultry and fur operations. Land used for intensive cultivation of vegetables and small fruits, includes market gardens, nurseries, flower and bulb farms and sod farms. Large scale commercial fur and poultry farms are also included because of their specialized agricultural nature.

owl:Class.dc:description: P - Improved pasture and forage crops
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: 'P' Improved pasture and forage crops.- Land used for improved pasture or for the production of hay and other cultivated fodder crops, including land being cleared for these purposes.

The LBCS recognizes different dimensions of Land Use: Activity, Function, Structure, Site, and Ownership Classifications. Each dimension is further defined by a taxonomy of specialized classifications. For each dimension, we introduce an equivalent class name for disambiguation, e.g. to distinguish between the Activity dimension of land use (we refer to this as ActivityClassification) and the notion of an Activity in icity.

Land Use Classifications provide a means of describing the land cover/use in a standard way. Various classification systems are used to identify types of land use. Currently, we include LBCS, CLUMP, and AAFC.
Added for organizational purposes, to identify all classes defined in the Land Use ontology.

owl:Class.dc:description: E - Mines, quarries, sand and gravel pits
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: 'E' Mines, quarries, sand and gravel pits, open excavations. Land used in the past or present for the extraction of earth materials.

owl:Class.dc:description: U - Non-productive woodland
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: 'U' Non-productive woodland. Land covered by scrub growth.

owl:Class.dc:description: G - Orchards and vineyards
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: 'G' Orchards and vineyards. Land used for the production of tree fruits, hops and grapes.
Rock, beaches, ice, barren land

owl:Class.dc:description: O - Outdoor recreation
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: 'O' Outdoor recreation - Land used for private or public outdoor recreational purposes. Some examples are: golf courses, parks, beaches, summer cottage areas, game preserves and historic sites.

owl:Class.dc:description: T - Productive woodland
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: 'T' Productive woodland.Wooded land with trees having over 25% canopy cover and being over 20 feet in height approximately. Artificially restocked areas, or plantations are included regardless of age. Much cut-over and burned-over land is included.
The population that resides within a given area (Parcel)
Primary, secondary and tertiary
Built-up and urban

owl:Class.dc:description: M - Swamp, marsh or bog
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: 'M' Swamp, marsh, or bog. Open wetlands except those which frequently dry up or show evidence of grazing or hay cutting.
Wetland with tree cover
Treed areas <1 ha in size
Areas not classified due to clouds.

owl:Class.dc:description: K - Unimproved pasture and range land
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: 'K' Rough grazing and range land. Areas of natural grasslands, sedges, herbaceous plants and abandoned farmland whether used for grazing or not. Bushes and trees may cover up to 25% of the area. Intermittently wet hay lands (sloughs or meadows) are included as long as the land is utilized. Within some grassy, open woodlands, bushes and trees may exceed 25% cover if the area is actively grazed and no other use dominates.

owl:Class.dc:description: 8 - Unmapped areas
L - Unproductive land - rock
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: 'L' Rock and other unvegetated surfaces - rock barrens, badlands, alkaline flats, gravel bars, eroded river banks, mine dumps. Unproductive land which does not support vegetation.

owl:Class.dc:description: S - Unproductive land - sand
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: 'S' Sand, sand bars, sand flats, dunes and beaches - Unproductive unconsolidated land which does not support vegetation.

owl:Class.dc:description: B - Urban built-up area
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: 'B' Built-up area. Land occupied by cities, towns, and villages, or by isolated units away from settlements such as manufacturing plants, rail yards, and military camps. Parks and other open spaces within built-up areas are also included.
Undifferentiated wetland
Wetland with grass cover
Wetland with shrub cover

owl:Class.dc:description: Business Establishment: A Business establishment is a physical location where a Firm conducts business. A Business Establishment has a Location and may have an address.

Employee: An Firm has some Employees, whom it employs for some Occupation. An Employee is a type of Organization Agent. An Employee may be employed at a particular Business Establishment. An Employee may be responsible for one or more Roles within the Organization. An Employee is employed by some Organization, unless the Person is self-employed. An Employee has a Wage/Salary and may work at some Location (this may be the location of the Firm, an alternate Location, or a Location that is subject to change).
Firm: A Firm is a type of organization. A Firm has an address and an industry type, and some Employees. A Firm may have a Business Establishment(s).

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: General Office / Clerical

owl:Class.dc:description: A goal represents some state or complex states, and allows for the representation of various groups' responsibilities.
Occupation: An Occupation is performed by some Person. An Occupation has a type (e.g. sales, skilled trades)
Added for organizational purposes, to identify classes defined in the iCity-Organization ontology.

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Professional / Management / Technical

owl:Class.dc:description: Role: A Role has a single (possibly complex) Goal. A Role has some authority, requires some skill, and may also have some associated processes.

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Retail Sales and Service
Manufacturing / Construction / Trades

owl:Class.dc:description: A Person may have a unique identifier. A Person has a date of birth, and may have a date of death. A Person may be a member of a Family and/or a Household. A Person has a mother and father, and may have a spouse and/or child(ren). Note that we define the parent relation as the legal relation as opposed to biological. This property may be specialized and restricted, for example hasBiologicalMother: exactly 1 Person. A Person may have some Job and associated Income. A Person may have access to some Vehicle. A Person may have access to some Bicycle. A Person may have some TransitPass. A Person has an address of residence and may have other contact information such as E-mail, phone number, etcetera. A Person has a Schedule for a given point (period) in time. Note that some properties are not defined in the Person ontology, but in an extension of the Person ontology that captures the interaction between iCity domain ontologies (e.g. Persons and their Vehicles)
Added for organizational purposes, to identify classes defined in the Person ontology.
A Qualification captures some official degree of accomplishment. It may be required for something and/or possessed by some Person.
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: To be defined in greater detail in future versions. Likely to be defined in a separate ontology.

owl:Class.dc:description: Added for organizational purposes, to capture the classes reused from Schema.org. Notice that since we cannot import schema.org we must manually reference the individual IRIs.
A Skill captures an ability to perfom some activity or set of activities.
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: To be defined in greater detail in future versions. Likely to be defined in a separate ontology.

owl:Class.dc:description: Household as defined in the GCIShelters Ontology
Organization Agent: Members of an organization. Organization Agents have goals, authority, and may be members of some team. An Organization Agent plays a Role within the Organization.

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: An actuatable quality (property, characteristic) of a FeatureOfInterest.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Actuatable Property
owl:Class.skos:definition: An actuatable quality (property, characteristic) of a FeatureOfInterest.
owl:Class.skos:example: A window actuator acts by changing the state between a frame and a window. The ability of the window to be opened and closed is its ActuatableProperty.

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: An Actuation carries out an (Actuation) Procedure to change the state of the world using an Actuator.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Actuation
owl:Class.skos:definition: An Actuation carries out an (Actuation) Procedure to change the state of the world using an Actuator.
owl:Class.skos:example: The activity of automatically closing a window if the temperature in a room drops below 20 degree Celsius. The activity is the Actuation and the device that closes the window is the Actuator. The Procedure is the rule, plan, or specification that defines the conditions that triggers the Actuation, here a drop in temperature.

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A device that is used by, or implements, an (Actuation) Procedure that changes the state of the world.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Actuator
owl:Class.skos:definition: A device that is used by, or implements, an (Actuation) Procedure that changes the state of the world.
owl:Class.skos:example: A window actuator for automatic window control, i.e., opening or closing the window.

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: The thing whose property is being estimated or calculated in the course of an Observation to arrive at a Result or whose property is being manipulated by an Actuator, or which is being sampled or transformed in an act of Sampling.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Feature Of Interest
owl:Class.skos:definition: The thing whose property is being estimated or calculated in the course of an Observation to arrive at a Result or whose property is being manipulated by an Actuator, or which is being sampled or transformed in an act of Sampling.
owl:Class.skos:example: When measuring the height of a tree, the height is the observed ObservableProperty, 20m may be the Result of the Observation, and the tree is the FeatureOfInterest. A window is a FeatureOfInterest for an automatic window control Actuator.

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: An observable quality (property, characteristic) of a FeatureOfInterest.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Observable Property
owl:Class.skos:definition: An observable quality (property, characteristic) of a FeatureOfInterest.
owl:Class.skos:example: The height of a tree, the depth of a water body, or the temperature of a surface are examples of observable properties, while the value of a classic car is not (directly) observable but asserted.

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Act of carrying out an (Observation) Procedure to estimate or calculate a value of a property of a FeatureOfInterest. Links to a Sensor to describe what made the Observation and how; links to an ObservableProperty to describe what the result is an estimate of, and to a FeatureOfInterest to detail what that property was associated with.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Observation
owl:Class.skos:definition: Act of carrying out an (Observation) Procedure to estimate or calculate a value of a property of a FeatureOfInterest. Links to a Sensor to describe what made the Observation and how; links to an ObservableProperty to describe what the result is an estimate of, and to a FeatureOfInterest to detail what that property was associated with.
owl:Class.skos:example: The activity of estimating the intensity of an Earthquake using the Mercalli intensity scale is an Observation as is measuring the moment magnitude, i.e., the energy released by said earthquake.

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A Platform is an entity that hosts other entities, particularly Sensors, Actuators, Samplers, and other Platforms.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Platform
owl:Class.skos:definition: A Platform is an entity that hosts other entities, particularly Sensors, Actuators, Samplers, and other Platforms.
owl:Class.skos:example: A post, buoy, vehicle, ship, aircraft, satellite, cell-phone, human or animal may act as platforms for (technical or biological) sensors or actuators.

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A workflow, protocol, plan, algorithm, or computational method specifying how to make an Observation, create a Sample, or make a change to the state of the world (via an Actuator). A Procedure is re-usable, and might be involved in many Observations, Samplings, or Actuations. It explains the steps to be carried out to arrive at reproducible results.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Procedure
owl:Class.skos:definition: A workflow, protocol, plan, algorithm, or computational method specifying how to make an Observation, create a Sample, or make a change to the state of the world (via an Actuator). A Procedure is re-usable, and might be involved in many Observations, Samplings, or Actuations. It explains the steps to be carried out to arrive at reproducible results.
owl:Class.skos:example: The measured wind speed differs depending on the height of the sensor above the surface, e.g., due to friction. Consequently, procedures for measuring wind speed define a standard height for anemometers above ground, typically 10m for meteorological measures and 2m in Agrometeorology. This definition of height, sensor placement, and so forth are defined by the Procedure.
owl:Class.skos:note: Many observations may be created via the same Procedure, the same way as many tables are assembled using the same instructions (as information objects, not their concrete realization).

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: The Result of an Observation, Actuation, or act of Sampling. To store an observation's simple result value one can use the hasSimpleResult property.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Result
owl:Class.skos:definition: The Result of an Observation, Actuation, or act of Sampling. To store an observation's simple result value one can use the hasSimpleResult property.
owl:Class.skos:example: The value 20 as the height of a certain tree together with the unit, e.g., Meter.

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A Sample is the result from an act of Sampling.
Feature which is intended to be representative of a FeatureOfInterest on which Observations may be made.
Physical samples are sometimes known as 'specimens'.

Samples are artifacts of an observational strategy, and have no significant function outside of their role in the observation process. The characteristics of the samples themselves are of little interest, except perhaps to the manager of a sampling campaign.
A Sample is intended to sample some FatureOfInterest, so there is an expectation of at least one isSampleOf property. However, in some cases the identity, and even the exact type, of the sampled feature may not be known when observations are made using the sampling features.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Sample
owl:Class.skos:definition: Feature which is intended to be representative of a FeatureOfInterest on which Observations may be made.
owl:Class.skos:example: A 'station' is essentially an identifiable locality where a sensor system or Procedure may be deployed and an observation made. In the context of the observation model, it connotes the 'world in the vicinity of the station', so the observed properties relate to the physical medium at the station, and not to any physical artifact such as a mooring, buoy, benchmark, monument, well, etc.

A statistical sample is often designed to be characteristic of an entire population, so that observations can be made regarding the sample that provide a good estimate of the properties of the population.
owl:Class.skos:note: A transient sample, such as a ships-track or flight-line, might be identified and described, but is unlikely to be revisited exactly.

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A device that is used by, or implements, a Sampling Procedure to create or transform one or more samples.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Sampler
owl:Class.skos:definition: A device that is used by, or implements, a Sampling Procedure to create or transform one or more samples.
owl:Class.skos:example: A ball mill, diamond drill, hammer, hypodermic syringe and needle, image Sensor or a soil auger can all act as sampling devices (i.e., be Samplers). However, sometimes the distinction between the Sampler and the Sensor is not evident, as they are packaged as a unit. A Sampler need not be a physical device.

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: An act of Sampling carries out a sampling Procedure to create or transform one or more samples.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Sampling
owl:Class.skos:definition: An act of Sampling carries out a sampling Procedure to create or transform one or more samples.
owl:Class.skos:example: Crushing a rock sample in a ball mill.
Digging a pit through a soil sequence.
Dividing a field site into quadrants.
Drawing blood from a patient.
Drilling an observation well.
Establishing a station for environmental monitoring.
Registering an image of the landscape.
Selecting a subset of a population.
Sieving a powder to separate the subset finer than 100-mesh.
Splitting a piece of drill-core to create two new samples.
Taking a diamond-drill core from a rock outcrop.

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Device, agent (including humans), or software (simulation) involved in, or implementing, a Procedure. Sensors respond to a stimulus, e.g., a change in the environment, or input data composed from the results of prior Observations, and generate a Result. Sensors can be hosted by Platforms.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Sensor
owl:Class.skos:definition: Device, agent (including humans), or software (simulation) involved in, or implementing, a (Sensing) Procedure. Sensors respond to a stimulus, e.g., a change in the environment, or input data composed from the results of prior Observations, and generate a Result. Sensors can be hosted by Platforms.
owl:Class.skos:example: Accelerometers, gyroscopes, barometers, magnetometers, and so forth are Sensors that are typically mounted on a modern smart phone (which acts as Platform). Other examples of sensors include the human eyes.

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Describes the Deployment of one or more Systems for a particular purpose. Deployment may be done on a Platform.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Deployment
owl:Class.skos:definition: Describes the Deployment of one or more Systems for a particular purpose. Deployment may be done on a Platform.
owl:Class.skos:example: For example, a temperature Sensor deployed on a wall, or a whole network of Sensors deployed for an Observation campaign.

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Any information that is provided to a Procedure for its use.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Input
owl:Class.skos:definition: Any information that is provided to a Procedure for its use.

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Any information that is reported from a Procedure.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Output
owl:Class.skos:definition: Any information that is reported from a Procedure.

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A quality of an entity. An aspect of an entity that is intrinsic to and cannot exist without the entity.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Property
owl:Class.skos:definition: A quality of an entity. An aspect of an entity that is intrinsic to and cannot exist without the entity.

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: An event in the real world that 'triggers' the Sensor. The properties associated to the Stimulus may be different to the eventual observed ObservableProperty. It is the event, not the object, that triggers the Sensor.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Stimulus
owl:Class.skos:definition: An event in the real world that 'triggers' the Sensor. The properties associated to the Stimulus may be different to the eventual observed ObservableProperty. It is the event, not the object, that triggers the Sensor.

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: System is a unit of abstraction for pieces of infrastructure that implements Procedures. A System may have components, its subsystems, which are other systems.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: System
owl:Class.skos:definition: System is a unit of abstraction for pieces of infrastructure that implement Procedures. A System may have components, its subsystems, which are other systems.
